                <head>No. 367.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hale</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Thomas</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1872-09-26">
                            <hi rend="italic">September</hi> 26, 1872</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 8.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Your dispatch No. 2, under date of July 26,
                    relating to recent political disturbances in Peru, has been received.</p>
                <p>The indignation of the people of Peru at a cruel assassination and an attempted
                    usurpation and overthrow of a representative government commands admiration, and
                    their calm return to order gives promise of a stable condition of public
                    affairs.</p>
                <p>Your reply to the circular-note of Doctor Caso’s is approved.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>CHARLES HALE,<lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Acting Secretary.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
